<article>
    <h1>TAN YANG ER, MULTIDISCI&#xAD;PLINARY ARTIST AND SET DE&#xAD;SIGNER</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201024/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-24"><time>2020-10-24</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE HOME AND GARDEN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The lack of for­mal art train­ing has not stopped self-taught Tan from build­ing an im­pres­sive re­sume that ranges from in­stal­la­tion to set de­sign to art di­rect­ing.</p>
    <p>For starters, the 27-year-old’s works have gained in­ter­na­tional recog­ni­tion. She was named Best Vis­ual Art Direc­tor at the Mnet Asian</p>
    <p>Mu­sic Awards in South Korea for her work on the set of The Sam Wil­lows’ Keep Me Jeal­ous mu­sic video.</p>
    <p>Apart from work­ing with heavy­weights like Sin­ga­pore Air­lines, Sony Mu­sic and beauty la­bel Guer­lain un­der her prac­tice Yanger­meis­ter Studios, she also scored a gig as a pro­duc­tion de­signer for the tele­vi­sion se­ries Mixed Sig­nals (above).</p>
    <p>Keep an eye out for more of her public art in­stal­la­tions like her pre­vi­ous interactiv­e ASMR Won­der­land cre­ation on Sen­tosa.</p>
    <p>Info: Go to @yanger­meis­ter_ on In­sta­gram</p>

